0:22 - Let's start by talking about the questions we'll answer in this video, and I'm sure they won't be a surprise. The first question is, how do we interpret the parameters of a sampling distribution of a difference in sample means? And second, how do we calculate and interpret probabilities involving a sampling distribution of a difference in sample means?

0:45 - Now let's take a look at an example. You'll recognize this example from the previous video. A large tree produces lemons with weights that are approximately normally distributed with a mean of 4 ounces and a standard deviation of 0.5 ounces. A different tree produces oranges with weights that are approximately normally distributed with a mean of 3 ounces and a standard deviation of 0.4 ounces. Suppose we randomly select six fruit from each tree, calculate the mean weight for each sample, and compute the difference in sample means, x-bar L minus x-bar O.

1:20 - That is, we find the average weight of the six lemons, and then we find the average weight of the six oranges, and then we subtract those two averages. And then we do that a bunch of times. Here's the results of doing that 500 times. You can see that the distribution of x-bar L minus x-bar O is approximately normal. It has a mean of 1 ounce, that's the difference in the two population means. And it has a standard deviation of 0.26 ounces. Again, you learned that formula and how to do this calculation in the previous video.

1:54 - Now let's talk about interpreting the mean. Remember, the mean is mu sub x-bar L minus x-bar O, and that equals 1. Well, for all random samples of six lemons from the lemon tree and six oranges from the orange tree, the differences (L - O) in sample mean weight will have a mean of 1 ounce. You can see that roughly half the differences are bigger than 1 and roughly half are less than 1. And so if we were to find all of those differences and then find the average of all of those differences, it would equal 1.

2:27 - Notice also in our interpretation, we specified the order of subtraction as L minus O. If we had subtracted the oranges minus the lemons, then the mean would have been negative 1. So it's really important to specify which order you're subtracting in.

2:43 - Now let's talk about interpreting the standard deviation. Remember, the standard deviation of x-bar L minus x-bar O is equal to 0.26. So, for all random samples of six lemons from the lemon tree and six oranges from the orange tree, the differences (L - O) in sample mean weight will typically vary by about 0.26 ounces from the true difference in means of 1 ounce. Again, you can see that some of the dots are really close to 1. Other dots are quite far away. The 0.26 measures how far those dots are typically or on average from the mean.

3:19 - And finally, remember that knowing how much a sample statistic typically varies from the truth is one of the most important reasons we study sampling distributions. And you'll see this show up when we learn about confidence intervals in units 6 through 9.

3:33 - Now let's talk about calculating probabilities. Suppose we selected a random sample of six oranges and six lemons from these trees. Would it be unusual to get a sample mean weight for the lemons that was more than 1.2 ounces greater than the sample mean weight for the oranges? Well, what we're trying to find is the probability that x-bar L minus x-bar O is greater than 1.2.

